var ROWS = [{"id": "PY-F-01", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "07", "difficulty": "3", "template": "misconception", "question": "def add(x, items=[]): items.append(x); return items. You call add(1) then add(2). What comes back?", "optA": "[1] then [2] (a fresh list each call)", "optB": "[1] then [1, 2] (the default list persists across calls)", "optC": "an error on the second call", "optD": "[2] then [1, 2]", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "Default arguments are evaluated once, at definition time. The same list object is reused, so appends accumulate. Use items=None and create a new list inside the function.", "feedback_wrong": "A assumes a fresh default per call, but the default is built once at def time (B). It does not error (C), and the order is [1] then [1,2], not D."}, {"id": "PY-F-02", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "02", "difficulty": "2", "template": "misconception", "question": "What is the difference between == and is in Python?", "optA": "they are interchangeable", "optB": "== compares values; is compares object identity (same object in memory)", "optC": "is compares values; == compares identity", "optD": "is only works on numbers", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "== asks 'are the values equal?'; is asks 'are these the exact same object?'. Use == for value checks and reserve is for None and other singletons.", "feedback_wrong": "They are not interchangeable (A) and C has them backwards. is works on any object (D). Small-int/string caching can make is seem to work by accident - do not rely on it."}, {"id": "PY-F-03", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "03", "difficulty": "2", "template": "predict", "question": "a = [1, 2, 3]; b = a; b.append(4). What is a now?", "optA": "[1, 2, 3] (b is a separate copy)", "optB": "[1, 2, 3, 4] (a and b refer to the same list)", "optC": "an error", "optD": "[4]", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "Assignment binds another name to the same object; it does not copy. b and a are one list, so the append shows in both. Use a.copy() or list(a) for a real copy.", "feedback_wrong": "b = a does not copy (A). No error (C). Both names point to one list, so a becomes [1,2,3,4] (B), not D."}, {"id": "PY-F-04", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "06", "difficulty": "1", "template": "misconception", "question": "Which of these is truthy (evaluates to True in an if)?", "optA": "[] (empty list)", "optB": "0", "optC": "[0] (a list containing a zero)", "optD": "'' (empty string)", "correct": "C", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "Empty containers, 0, '', and None are all falsy. A non-empty list like [0] is truthy - it has one element, even though that element is 0.", "feedback_wrong": "Empty list (A), 0 (B), and empty string (D) are all falsy. Only the non-empty [0] is truthy - emptiness, not content, decides."}, {"id": "PY-F-05", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "03", "difficulty": "1", "template": "misconception", "question": "s = 'hello'; s.upper(). After this line, what is s?", "optA": "'HELLO' (upper modifies s in place)", "optB": "'hello' (strings are immutable; upper returns a new string)", "optC": "an error", "optD": "None", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "Strings are immutable. s.upper() returns a NEW string and leaves s unchanged. To keep the result, write s = s.upper().", "feedback_wrong": "Methods like upper() cannot modify a string in place (A). It returns a value, not None (D), and does not error (C)."}, {"id": "PY-F-06", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "08", "difficulty": "2", "template": "predict", "question": "In Python 3, what does map(str, [1, 2, 3]) return?", "optA": "the list ['1', '2', '3']", "optB": "a lazy map iterator that yields the values once when consumed", "optC": "a tuple", "optD": "it prints the values immediately", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "In Python 3, map (and filter) return lazy iterators, not lists. Wrap in list(...) to materialize, and remember they are exhausted after one pass.", "feedback_wrong": "It is not a list (A) - that was Python 2 - nor a tuple (C). Nothing is printed (D); it computes only when iterated."}, {"id": "PY-F-07", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "02", "difficulty": "2", "template": "misconception", "question": "What does the expression 0 or 'hi' evaluate to?", "optA": "True", "optB": "'hi' (or returns the first truthy operand, not a boolean)", "optC": "False", "optD": "0", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "and/or return one of their operands, not a bool. 'or' returns the first truthy value: 0 is falsy, so the result is 'hi'. This is what powers the 'x or default' idiom.", "feedback_wrong": "They return operands, not booleans (A, C). It skips the falsy 0 and returns 'hi', not 0 (D)."}, {"id": "PY-F-08", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "01", "difficulty": "1", "template": "compare", "question": "In Python 3, what are the result and type of 7 / 2 versus 7 // 2?", "optA": "both give 3 (int)", "optB": "7/2 = 3.5 (float), 7//2 = 3 (int, floor division)", "optC": "7/2 = 3 (int), 7//2 = 3.5 (float)", "optD": "both give 3.5 (float)", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "/ is true division and always returns a float (3.5). // is floor division, returning the floored value (3), as an int here.", "feedback_wrong": "In Python 3, / never truncates to int (A), and C is reversed. // floors rather than giving a float (D)."}, {"id": "PY-F-09", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "06", "difficulty": "3", "template": "predict", "question": "a = [[1, 2], [3, 4]]; b = a.copy(); b[0].append(99). What is a[0]?", "optA": "[1, 2] (the copy is fully independent)", "optB": "[1, 2, 99] (the copy is shallow; inner lists are shared)", "optC": "an error", "optD": "[99]", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "list.copy() is a shallow copy: the outer list is new, but the inner lists are the same objects. Mutating an inner list shows in both. Use copy.deepcopy for full independence.", "feedback_wrong": "A shallow copy does not copy nested objects (A). No error (C). The inner list is shared, so a[0] becomes [1,2,99] (B)."}, {"id": "PY-F-10", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "06", "difficulty": "2", "template": "misconception", "question": "Which of these can NOT be used as a dictionary key?", "optA": "a string", "optB": "a tuple of numbers", "optC": "a list", "optD": "an integer", "correct": "C", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "Dict keys must be hashable, which in practice means immutable. Lists are mutable and unhashable, so they cannot be keys. Strings, numbers, and tuples of hashables can.", "feedback_wrong": "Strings (A), tuples of numbers (B), and ints (D) are all hashable, valid keys. Only the mutable list (C) is unhashable."}, {"id": "PY-F-11", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "05", "difficulty": "2", "template": "predict", "question": "What does [x*x for x in range(4)] produce?", "optA": "a lazy generator object", "optB": "[0, 1, 4, 9] (a list, built eagerly)", "optC": "{0, 1, 4, 9} (a set)", "optD": "it modifies range in place", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "A list comprehension eagerly builds and returns a new list: [0,1,4,9]. Use (...) for a lazy generator or {...} for a set/dict comprehension.", "feedback_wrong": "Square brackets build a list now, not a lazy generator (A - that needs ()), and not a set (C - needs {}). It does not mutate range (D)."}, {"id": "PY-F-12", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "06", "difficulty": "1", "template": "misconception", "question": "What is set([1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3])?", "optA": "[1, 2, 3] (a list)", "optB": "{1, 2, 3} (a set with duplicates removed, unordered)", "optC": "{1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3}", "optD": "an error because of the duplicates", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "A set stores unique, unordered elements, so duplicates collapse to {1, 2, 3}. Sets are ideal for membership tests and deduplication.", "feedback_wrong": "It returns a set, not a list (A). Duplicates are removed, so not C. Duplicate input is fine, no error (D)."}, {"id": "PY-F-13", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "07", "difficulty": "2", "template": "misconception", "question": "In def f(*args, **kwargs):, what are args and kwargs?", "optA": "both are lists", "optB": "args is a tuple of positional arguments; kwargs is a dict of keyword arguments", "optC": "args is a dict; kwargs is a tuple", "optD": "they are reserved keywords you cannot rename", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "*args collects extra positional args into a tuple; **kwargs collects extra keyword args into a dict. The names are convention - the * and ** are what matter.", "feedback_wrong": "args is a tuple, not a list (A), and C swaps them. The names are conventional, not reserved (D)."}, {"id": "PY-F-14", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "05", "difficulty": "2", "template": "predict", "question": "For s = 'abcde', what is s[::-1]?", "optA": "'abcde'", "optB": "'edcba' (a reversed copy via step -1)", "optC": "an error", "optD": "'e'", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "The slice [start:stop:step] with step -1 walks backward, producing a reversed copy: 'edcba'. Slicing never mutates; it returns a new sequence.", "feedback_wrong": "Step -1 reverses, so not unchanged (A). It is valid syntax, no error (C). It is the whole reversed string, not one char (D)."}, {"id": "PY-F-15", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "06", "difficulty": "3", "template": "predict", "question": "t = ([1, 2], 3); t[0].append(99). What happens?", "optA": "an error - tuples are immutable", "optB": "it works: t becomes ([1, 2, 99], 3) - the tuple is fixed but its list element is mutable", "optC": "t becomes ([1, 2], 3, 99)", "optD": "it silently does nothing", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "A tuple's immutability means you cannot reassign its slots, but if a slot holds a mutable object (a list), you can still mutate that object. So t[0].append works.", "feedback_wrong": "Mutating the contained list is allowed (A); only t[0] = ... would fail. The append goes into the inner list, not the tuple (C), and it does take effect (D)."}, {"id": "PY-F-16", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "07", "difficulty": "2", "template": "predict", "question": "def add_item(lst): lst.append(1). You call add_item(my) on your list my = []. What is my afterward?", "optA": "[] (the function received a copy)", "optB": "[1] (lists are passed by reference; the function mutated your list)", "optC": "an error", "optD": "None", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "Python passes object references. The function received the same list object, so appending inside changes your list. To avoid this, copy inside or pass lst[:].", "feedback_wrong": "It is not a copy (A). No error (C). The function returns None, but my itself becomes [1] (D confuses the return value with the list)."}, {"id": "PY-F-17", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "06", "difficulty": "2", "template": "predict", "question": "d = {'a': 1}. What is the difference between d['b'] and d.get('b')?", "optA": "both return None", "optB": "d['b'] raises KeyError; d.get('b') returns None (or a default you pass)", "optC": "both raise KeyError", "optD": "both return 0", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "Indexing a missing key raises KeyError; .get returns None, or .get('b', default) returns your fallback. Use .get when a missing key is expected.", "feedback_wrong": "d['b'] does not return None (A) - it raises. .get does not raise (C). Neither defaults to 0 unless asked (D)."}, {"id": "PY-F-18", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "08", "difficulty": "2", "template": "match", "question": "To sort a list of (name, age) tuples by age, what do you pass to sorted?", "optA": "sorted(data, reverse=True)", "optB": "sorted(data, key=lambda t: t[1])", "optC": "sorted(data, key=t[1])", "optD": "sorted(data.age)", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "key takes a function applied to each element to produce the sort value. lambda t: t[1] extracts the age, and the list is ordered by it.", "feedback_wrong": "reverse alone does not pick a field (A). key needs a function, not a bare expression (C). Tuples have no .age attribute (D)."}, {"id": "PY-F-19", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "05", "difficulty": "1", "template": "match", "question": "You want both the index and the value while looping over a list. What is the idiomatic tool?", "optA": "range(len(lst)) and index manually", "optB": "for i, v in enumerate(lst)", "optC": "zip(lst, lst)", "optD": "lst.items()", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "enumerate(lst) yields (index, value) pairs, cleaner than indexing with range(len(...)). zip pairs multiple iterables; .items() is for dicts, not lists.", "feedback_wrong": "range(len(...)) works but is not idiomatic (A). zip(lst, lst) pairs the list with itself (C). Lists have no .items() (D)."}, {"id": "PY-F-20", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "06", "difficulty": "2", "template": "compare", "question": "For many 'x in collection' lookups on large data, which is faster - a set or a list - and why?", "optA": "list, because it preserves order", "optB": "set, because membership is O(1) average (hashing) vs O(n) scan for a list", "optC": "they are identical", "optD": "list, because sets cannot do 'in'", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "Sets (and dict keys) use hashing for average O(1) membership; a list must scan element by element, O(n). For many lookups, convert to a set.", "feedback_wrong": "Order does not help lookup speed (A). They are not identical for large n (C). Lists do support 'in', just slowly (D)."}, {"id": "PY-F-21", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "08", "difficulty": "3", "template": "predict", "question": "funcs = [lambda: i for i in range(3)]. What does [f() for f in funcs] return?", "optA": "[0, 1, 2]", "optB": "[2, 2, 2] - the lambdas capture the variable i, which is 2 after the loop ends", "optC": "an error", "optD": "[0, 0, 0]", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "Closures capture the variable, not its value at creation time. By the time the lambdas run, i is 2, so all return 2. Fix with a default arg: lambda i=i: i.", "feedback_wrong": "They do not capture per-iteration values (A, D). No error (C). All three see the final i = 2 (B)."}, {"id": "PY-F-22", "area": "fundamentals", "module": "03", "difficulty": "2", "template": "predict", "question": "In Python 3, does range(1000000) build a list of a million ints?", "optA": "yes, it creates the full list immediately", "optB": "no, range is a lazy sequence that computes values on demand, using O(1) memory", "optC": "it raises a MemoryError", "optD": "it returns a generator that is exhausted after one pass", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "range is a lazy, reusable sequence: it stores start/stop/step and computes values as needed, so it uses constant memory regardless of size. Wrap in list() only if you need all values.", "feedback_wrong": "It does not build a list (A) or run out of memory (C). Unlike a generator, range is reusable, not one-shot (D)."}, {"id": "PY-O-01", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "14", "difficulty": "3", "template": "predict", "question": "A class has a class-level attribute tags = [] shared by all instances. One instance does self.tags.append('x'). What do other instances see?", "optA": "only that instance has 'x'; others stay []", "optB": "all instances see ['x'], because the list is shared at the class level", "optC": "it raises an error", "optD": "a new per-instance list is created automatically", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "A mutable class attribute is shared by every instance until one rebinds it. Appending mutates the single shared list, so all instances see it. Initialize mutable state in __init__ instead.", "feedback_wrong": "It is not per-instance (A, D) - class attributes are shared. No error (C). The shared list now holds 'x' for everyone (B)."}, {"id": "PY-O-02", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "15", "difficulty": "2", "template": "match", "question": "What is the intended difference between __str__ and __repr__?", "optA": "they are identical", "optB": "__str__ is a readable form for users; __repr__ is an unambiguous form for developers/debugging", "optC": "__repr__ is for users; __str__ is for developers", "optD": "__str__ is required and __repr__ is forbidden", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "__str__ targets end users (readable); __repr__ targets developers and should be unambiguous (ideally eval-able). If __str__ is missing, Python falls back to __repr__.", "feedback_wrong": "They serve different audiences (A) and C swaps them. Both are allowed; __repr__ is the sensible fallback (D)."}, {"id": "PY-O-03", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "16", "difficulty": "2", "template": "misconception", "question": "What does the @property decorator let you do?", "optA": "make a method run twice", "optB": "access a method like an attribute (obj.x, not obj.x()), enabling computed or validated attributes", "optC": "make an attribute private", "optD": "turn a function into a class", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "@property exposes a method as if it were a plain attribute, so you can compute or validate on access without changing the calling syntax. Add a setter to control assignment.", "feedback_wrong": "It is not about running twice (A) or privacy (C - that is name mangling). It does not create a class (D). It is attribute-style access to a method (B)."}, {"id": "PY-O-04", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "15", "difficulty": "2", "template": "predict", "question": "Class B(A) overrides method foo and does not call super(). When you call foo() on a B instance, which runs?", "optA": "A.foo only", "optB": "B.foo only (the override replaces it unless you call super)", "optC": "both, A.foo then B.foo automatically", "optD": "it raises because of the conflict", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "An override replaces the parent method for that class. The parent's version runs only if you explicitly call super().foo(); Python does not chain them automatically.", "feedback_wrong": "The override takes precedence, so A.foo alone is wrong (A). Nothing runs both automatically (C). Overriding is normal, not an error (D)."}, {"id": "PY-O-05", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "16", "difficulty": "2", "template": "misconception", "question": "What does a leading double underscore (e.g. self.__secret) actually do?", "optA": "makes the attribute truly private and inaccessible", "optB": "triggers name mangling to _ClassName__secret, discouraging but not preventing outside access", "optC": "deletes the attribute after use", "optD": "makes it a class variable", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "A double underscore triggers name mangling, mainly to avoid name clashes in subclasses. It is a convention/speed bump, not real privacy - you can still reach _ClassName__secret.", "feedback_wrong": "Python has no truly private attributes (A). It is not deleted (C) or made class-level (D); it is renamed to discourage access (B)."}, {"id": "PY-O-06", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "17", "difficulty": "2", "template": "predict", "question": "g = (x for x in range(3)). You call list(g), then list(g) again. What does the second call return?", "optA": "[0, 1, 2] again", "optB": "[] because a generator is exhausted after one full pass", "optC": "an error", "optD": "[0, 1, 2, 0, 1, 2]", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "Generators are one-shot iterators. After the first list(g) consumes it, it is exhausted and yields nothing, so the second call returns []. Rebuild the generator to iterate again.", "feedback_wrong": "Generators do not restart (A, D). It is not an error (C); an exhausted generator simply yields nothing (B)."}, {"id": "PY-O-07", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "13", "difficulty": "2", "template": "misconception", "question": "What does a decorator (@my_decorator above a function) do?", "optA": "runs the function immediately at definition time", "optB": "wraps the function, replacing it with a new function that usually calls the original", "optC": "makes the function private", "optD": "documents the function only, with no runtime effect", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "A decorator takes the function and returns a (usually wrapping) function bound to the same name, adding behavior - logging, timing, caching - around the original call.", "feedback_wrong": "It does not call the function at def time (A). It is not about privacy (C) and is not a no-op (D); it actively replaces the function (B)."}, {"id": "PY-O-08", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "11", "difficulty": "2", "template": "misconception", "question": "In try/except/finally, when does the finally block run?", "optA": "only if no exception was raised", "optB": "only if an exception was raised", "optC": "always - whether or not an exception occurred, even if the try block returns", "optD": "only if you call it manually", "correct": "C", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "finally always runs - on success, on a handled or unhandled exception, even when the try block returns. It is for cleanup that must happen no matter what.", "feedback_wrong": "It is not conditional on success (A) or failure (B), and it runs automatically, not manually (D). 'Always' is the point (C)."}, {"id": "PY-O-09", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "17", "difficulty": "2", "template": "match", "question": "What does a with block (context manager) guarantee?", "optA": "the code runs faster", "optB": "the resource's cleanup (__exit__) runs even if an exception occurs inside the block", "optC": "the block runs in parallel", "optD": "exceptions inside are silently ignored", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "A context manager runs __enter__ on entry and guarantees __exit__ on exit, even if the body raises. That is why 'with open(...)' reliably closes the file.", "feedback_wrong": "It is not about speed (A) or parallelism (C). It does not swallow exceptions by default (D); it guarantees cleanup (B)."}, {"id": "PY-O-10", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "17", "difficulty": "2", "template": "match", "question": "What does @dataclass give you for a class?", "optA": "it makes the class abstract", "optB": "it auto-generates __init__, __repr__, and __eq__ from the declared fields", "optC": "it makes all fields private", "optD": "it prevents inheritance", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "@dataclass synthesizes boilerplate - __init__, __repr__, __eq__ and more - from typed field declarations, so you write less plumbing. frozen=True makes instances immutable.", "feedback_wrong": "It is not about abstractness (A), privacy (C), or blocking inheritance (D). It generates the boilerplate methods (B)."}, {"id": "PY-O-11", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "17", "difficulty": "2", "template": "misconception", "question": "What is the difference between an iterable and an iterator?", "optA": "they are the same", "optB": "an iterable can produce an iterator (has __iter__); an iterator yields values one at a time (has __next__) and is consumed as it goes", "optC": "an iterator can be reused infinitely; an iterable cannot be looped", "optD": "only lists are iterable", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "An iterable (list, str, dict) hands out an iterator via __iter__. The iterator does the stepping via __next__ and is exhausted as consumed. A list is iterable but is not its own iterator.", "feedback_wrong": "They differ (A) and C is backwards (iterators exhaust). Many types are iterable, not just lists (D)."}, {"id": "PY-O-12", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "12", "difficulty": "2", "template": "misconception", "question": "What is the most common cause of a RecursionError (infinite recursion)?", "optA": "using recursion at all", "optB": "a missing or unreachable base case, so the function never stops calling itself", "optC": "returning a value too early", "optD": "Python does not support recursion", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "Every recursion needs a base case that stops the descent. Without one (or if it is never reached), calls stack until Python hits its recursion limit and raises RecursionError.", "feedback_wrong": "Recursion itself is fine (A). Returning early ends recursion safely (C). Python supports recursion, with a depth limit (D)."}, {"id": "PY-O-13", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "11", "difficulty": "2", "template": "misconception", "question": "Why is 'except Exception: pass' (a bare catch-all that ignores the error) usually bad practice?", "optA": "it is a syntax error", "optB": "it silently swallows all errors, including bugs you did not anticipate, hiding real problems", "optC": "it slows the program down", "optD": "you can only catch one exception ever", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "Catching everything and ignoring it hides genuine bugs (typos, logic errors) along with the one you expected. Catch the specific exception you can handle, and let the rest surface.", "feedback_wrong": "It is valid syntax (A) and not a speed issue (C). You can catch multiple types (D). The problem is masking real errors (B)."}, {"id": "PY-O-14", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "16", "difficulty": "2", "template": "match", "question": "What does inheriting from abc.ABC with an @abstractmethod do?", "optA": "nothing at runtime", "optB": "it forbids instantiating the base class and forces subclasses to implement the abstract methods", "optC": "it makes the class faster", "optD": "it automatically implements the methods for you", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "An abstract base class cannot be instantiated directly, and any concrete subclass must override every @abstractmethod or it too stays abstract. This enforces an interface contract.", "feedback_wrong": "It has real runtime effect (A). It does not implement methods for you (D) or affect speed (C); it enforces the contract (B)."}, {"id": "PY-O-15", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "14", "difficulty": "2", "template": "misconception", "question": "What is the difference between @classmethod and @staticmethod?", "optA": "they are the same", "optB": "a classmethod receives the class (cls) as its first arg; a staticmethod receives neither self nor cls", "optC": "a staticmethod receives self; a classmethod receives nothing", "optD": "both receive self", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "@classmethod gets cls (good for alternative constructors); @staticmethod gets no implicit first argument (just a function grouped under the class). Neither gets an instance.", "feedback_wrong": "They differ (A) and C is backwards. A regular method gets self; these do not (D). classmethod=cls, staticmethod=nothing (B)."}, {"id": "PY-O-16", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "15", "difficulty": "2", "template": "match", "question": "You define __len__ on your class. What does that enable?", "optA": "nothing; __len__ is ignored", "optB": "calling len(obj) on instances returns whatever __len__ returns", "optC": "it makes the object iterable", "optD": "it defines addition with +", "correct": "B", "points": "1", "feedback_correct": "Dunder methods hook into built-ins: __len__ backs len(obj), __eq__ powers ==, __add__ powers +, __iter__ makes it iterable. They let your objects behave like built-ins.", "feedback_wrong": "It is not ignored (A). Iteration is __iter__ (C); addition is __add__ (D). __len__ specifically backs len() (B)."}, {"id": "PY-O-17", "area": "oop_tooling", "module": "15", "difficulty": "3", "template": "predict", "question": "In diamond inheritance D(B, C) where both B and C inherit from A, what decides which method runs when D does not override it?", "optA": "a random choice", "optB": "the Method Resolution Order (MRO) - a 